Texas Game Wardens also appreciate the assistance provided during this investigation.  If you observe fishing or hunting related crime, please notify Operation Game Thief immediately at 800-792-GAME (4263) visit http://ogttx.com/contactus.cfm or call your local Game Warden. \r\n\r\nMedia Contact: Mike Cox, 512-389-8046, mike.cox@tpwd.texas.gov \r\n\r\nNov. 20, 2013\r\n\r\nTexas Game Wardens \u201cLike\u201d End Result of Angler\u2019s Facebook Post\r\n \r\nAUSTIN \u2013 A South Texas man has pled guilty to nine charges of possession of oversized red drum, one charge of no saltwater fishing license, and one charge of exceeding the possession limit for red drum.\r\n\r\nThe investigation leading to the filing of charges against 30-year-old Luis Castro began with a Facebook post showing a man holding a large red drum with eight other oversize drum on display in the bed of a pickup truck. (The bag limit for redfish is three per day, and they must be between 20 and 28 inches. Only one redfish longer than that can be kept, and only with a properly completed redfish tag attached to it.)\r\n\r\nOn Nov. 1, game wardens in Cameron County were contacted about the Facebook picture, which had originally been placed on line by Castro\u2019s brother. Accompanying the image was the comment, \u201cjust for fun.\u201d \r\n\r\nGame wardens ended up receiving multiple complaints regarding the Facebook post. TPWD dispatchers and game wardens were able to review records which eventually resulted in the positive identification of Castro and his place of employment. \r\n\r\nOn Nov. 6, game wardens interviewed Castro and obtained a signed written statement. Five days later, Willacy County Justice of the Peace George Solice issued an arrest warrant for Castro and game wardens arrested him the same day. Following arraignment, he was released with a court date of Nov. 19. \r\n \r\n\u201cAnglers on several social media sites were posting negative comments, and a day after the picture was originally posted, it was removed,\u201d said Game Warden Maj. Alan Teague. \u201cHowever, the picture had been saved by many anglers and reposted.\u201d\r\nTeague said the picture made it to fishing groups as far away as Florida. \u201cWith tips from anglers and hard work by our game wardens and dispatchers, we were able to track the individual to a city in South Texas,\u201d Teague said.\r\n\r\nDuring sentencing, Justice of the Peace Solice noted how important recreational fishing is to the people in Willacy County which includes Port Mansfield.  Before sentencing Castro, the judge pointed out that there are people in the county whose livelihood depends upon the quality and future of recreational fishing. \u201cIt was an obscene number of fish that you caught,\u201d the judge said to the defendant.  \u201cWe are all living paycheck-to-paycheck but none of us are going hungry.  It was completely unnecessary to take that many fish.\u201d  \r\n\r\nCastro was fined $2,600 and an additional $2,645.91 will be assessed as part of the civil restitution.  \r\n\r\nhttp://tpwd.texas.gov/newsmedia/releases/?req=20131120a", "application": {"name": "Photos", "id": "2305272732"}, "link": "https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=613087652082959&set=a.371233516268375.85229.362214707170256&type=1", "object_id": "613087652082959", "story_tags": {"0": [{"length": 41, "offset": 0, "type": "page", "id": "270115323088033", "name": "Texas A&M Wildlife and Fisheries Sciences"}], "49": [{"length": 18, "offset": 49, "type": "page", "id": "362214707170256", "name": "Texas Game Wardens"}]}, "created_time": "2013-11-21T14:51:38+0000", "message": "Don't violate fishing laws but if you do, don't post a picture on Facebook. A recent nationwide survey indicates 79 percent of Americans approve of hunting, marking a five percent increase from 2011 and the highest level since 1995.\n\nResponsive Management, a public opinion research organization focusing on natural resource and outdoor recreation issues, began to scientifically track nationwide hunting approval trends in 1995. The most recent finding of 79 percent is the highest percentage to date. Trends remain relatively steady over the years: 73 percent in 1995, 75 percent in 2003, 78 percent in 2006, 74 percent in 2011 and 79 percent in 2013. \n\nThe survey also found that more than half of Americans (52 percent) strongly approve of hunting (79 percent strongly or moderately approve) while 12 percent disapprove (strongly or moderately) of hunting. Another 9 percent gave a neutral answer."}

No fee is charged to watch our public hatchling releases.  \r\n\r\nHowever, only three clutches are advanced in hatching and sometimes hatching speeds up or slows down, necessitating cancellation of the scheduled public release. So before you come out to the release, MAKE SURE to check this Facebook page or call the Hatchling Hotline at 361-949-7163 to check if the turtles are ready for release on schedule. If the release must be cancelled we will post a cancellation message on this Facebook page and on our Hatchling Hotline.  If these cancellation messages have not been done by 2:00 am on Tuesday  July 30, then the release will be held as scheduled. \r\n\r\nRELEASE DIRECTIONS: The release will be held in front of the Malaquite Beach Visitor Center at Padre Island National Seashore.  To attend, follow park road 22 out to Padre Island National Seashore.  No fee is charged to attend the release.  If the National Seashore Entrance Station is open, identify that you are attending the release, and you will not be charged park entrance fees.  About two miles after the National Seashore Entrance Station, you will see a hatchling release sign on the right and the large Malaquite Beach Visitor Center parking lot on the left.  You should turn left there, park your vehicle in the large lot, and meet on the deck of the Visitor Center.  A park ranger will meet you there to deliver a program about the turtles and lead you to the release site.  However, the hatchling release sign and ranger will not be present until about 6:20 am.  \r\n\r\nAt the release, you should not bring or eat food since it will attract gulls, and you should not wear white colored clothing or white colored footwear or take photos using a flash, since all of these will disorient the hatchlings.\r\n\r\nAfter the release, you are welcome to visit our Visitor Center, which will before the end of the release. We have sea turtle and other educational displays, Adopt-A-Turtle packets, and other items for sale. If our Concessions store is open you will be able to purchase drinks, snacks, items to use on the beach, and souvenirs. Both can be accessed on the deck where you met for the program before the release. Eggs in 8 clutches laid on June 9 have begun to hatch, so there is a good chance that there will be a public release this weekend. The more clutches that hatch at one time the better chance that we will be able to hold a public release since if hatchlings from one or more clutches go into their frenzy in the middle of the night and must immediately be released, others may still be available for a public releases in the morning. This is the last large group of clutches laid on the same day that we are incubating this year.  \r\n\r\nOur releases are held at 6:45 am in front of the Visitor Center at Padre Island National Seashore, on North Padre Island, and are open to the public free-of-charge. We will announce the release on this Facebook page and on our Hatchling Hotline (tel. 361- 949-7163). This is sideoats grama, the state grass of Texas. Sideoats grama is a perennial warm season bunchgrass found throughout the United States. It grows 2-3 feet with an unbranched stem that is a blueish-green in the spring, and turns to a reddish-brown or straw color in the fall. The leaf blades are up to 8\" long and \u00bc\" across; they are light green to green, mostly hairless, and rough along their margins. Sideoats grama gets its name from the small oat-like seeds that hang down on one side of the seed stem. It is a good forage grass for livestock, and uncommon nesting site for bobwhites, and its seeds have limited value for bobwhites. This group of eight was part of a group of 16 that were found within a few feet of one another.  Texas horned lizards dig an underground chamber in which they lay their eggs. {"picture": "https://fbcdn-photos-g-a.akamaihd.net/hphotos-ak-ash3/t1.0-0/933957_10151393401416409_1278222107_s.jpg", "story": "Texas A&M Wildlife and Fisheries Sciences shared Brazos Valley Museum of Natural History's photo.", "from": {"category": "University", "name": "Texas A&M Wildlife and Fisheries Sciences", "category_list": [{"id": "108051929285833", "name": "College & University"}], "id": "270115323088033"}, "name": "Timeline Photos", "privacy": {"value": ""}, "actions": [{"link": "https://www.facebook.com/270115323088033/posts/361384603961104", "name": "Comment"}, {"link": "https://www.facebook.com/270115323088033/posts/361384603961104", "name": "Like"}], "properties": [{"text": "Brazos Valley Museum of Natural History", "href": "https://www.facebook.com/BrazosValleyMuseumOfNaturalHistory?ref=stream", "name": "By"}], "caption": "The Brazos Valley Museum of Natural History proudly announces its participation in BIOBLITZ, on Friday, April 26 and Saturday, April 27. This two-day event held at Lick Creek Park is FREE to the public, and begins Friday night at 6pm and goes until 9pm, with attendees participating in various night-time activities. The event continues with booths open all day Saturday from 10am-4pm. Activities participants can enjoy include lectures, a butterfly tent, solar viewing sessions, guided nature hikes, and much more!\r\n\r\nOrganized by the Society of Conservation Biology (TAMU), the event includes booths with kid friendly activities the whole family will enjoy! The Brazos Valley Museum of Natural History will have its own booth with live animals, both native and nonnative, a fossil/fossil replica match challenge, and a Test Your Texas Wildlife Knowledge activity board. Other organizations such as the Friends of Lick Creek Park, the Rio Brazos Audubon Society, the Wildlife Society (TAMU), the Entomology Club (TAMU), and the Brazos Chapter of the Texas Master Naturalists will be hosting fun and informative natural history activities.\r\n\r\nDuring BioBlitz, anyone from a budding scientist to an experienced naturalist is invited to join local biologists on a team to conduct a survey of Lick Creek Park and count as many different species native to the park as they can. The purpose of BioBlitz is to highlight the importance of urban green spaces to biodiversity and to the overall health of our local environment.\r\n\r\nLick Creek Park is a unique treasure of the Brazos Valley. This 515 acre park is home to an abundance of wildlife, including species of butterflies, birds, reptiles, amphibians, mammals that are difficult to find elsewhere. Lick Creek Park is also an important archeological site and provides historical information about how Native Americans and early settlers used the Brazos Valley. \r\n\r\nFor online information about BioBlitz please see: http://scb.tamu.edu/node/9 or the BioBlitz Coordinator at scbbioblitz@gmail.com.\r\nSee also the Friends of Lick Creek Park website for more park information: http://lickcreekpark.org .", "application": {"name": "Photos", "id": "2305272732"}, "link": "https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=10151393401416409&set=a.10150928327716409.406881.93572166408&type=1", "object_id": "10151393401416409", "story_tags": {"0": [{"length": 41, "offset": 0, "type": "page", "id": "270115323088033", "name": "Texas A&M Wildlife and Fisheries Sciences"}], "49": [{"length": 39, "offset": 49, "type": "page", "id": "93572166408", "name": "Brazos Valley Museum of Natural History"}]}, "created_time": "2013-04-26T18:39:41+0000", "message": "BioBlitz! {"picture": "https://fbcdn-photos-h-a.akamaihd.net/hphotos-ak-frc3/t1.0-0/599134_10151255459705834_1036684682_s.jpg", "story": "Texas A&M Wildlife and Fisheries Sciences shared Rolling Plains Quail Research Ranch's photo.", "likes": {"paging": {"cursors": {"after": "Njg3MDUyNzk=", "before": "Njg3MDUyNzk="}}, "data": [{"id": "68705279", "name": "Eric Bauer"}]}, "from": {"category": "University", "name": "Texas A&M Wildlife and Fisheries Sciences", "category_list": [{"id": "108051929285833", "name": "College & University"}], "id": "270115323088033"}, "name": "Timeline Photos", "privacy": {"value": ""}, "actions": [{"link": "https://www.facebook.com/270115323088033/posts/324812094288091", "name": "Comment"}, {"link": "https://www.facebook.com/270115323088033/posts/324812094288091", "name": "Like"}], "properties": [{"text": "Rolling Plains Quail Research Ranch", "href": "https://www.facebook.com/RPQRR?ref=stream", "name": "By"}], "caption": "We've been trapping quail on the ranch this past month in preparation for the breeding season. This week I caught my first scaled or \"blue\" quail. So far he's the only one we've caught, and I caught him three times over the course of a week in the same trap. Apparently he doesn't have any other little friends that he hangs out with. It's harder to tell the males and females of blue quail apart from one another, but this one appears to be a male (although I admit it's a questionable call; a female has distinct brown streaks down its throat; this one has faint lines so I'm calling it a male. {"from": {"category": "University", "name": "Texas A&M Wildlife and Fisheries Sciences", "category_list": [{"id": "108051929285833", "name": "College & University"}], "id": "270115323088033"}, "privacy": {"value": ""}, "actions": [{"link": "https://www.facebook.com/270115323088033/posts/341840819248816", "name": "Comment"}, {"link": "https://www.facebook.com/270115323088033/posts/341840819248816", "name": "Like"}], "updated_time": "2013-02-26T16:09:09+0000", "likes": {"paging": {"cursors": {"after": "NTcxMjExOTg2", "before": "MTAwMDAwMzUxMTQ0Mzgy"}}, "data": [{"id": "100000351144382", "name": "Emmanuel Chilala"}, {"id": "571211986", "name": "Erika Chairez"}]}, "created_time": "2013-02-26T16:09:09+0000", "message": "New date & time!\nWednesday, Feb. 27, Noon - 1:00 pm, 1400 MSC\nSecuring Our Water Future: The Imperative for Urban-Rural Partnerships presented by Dr. Brian Richter, The Nature Conservancy\n\nIf you\u2019re a university student today, you can expect that during your lifetime you\u2019ll be sharing the planet with more than 9 billion people. More than 2/3 of that global population will be living in cities; in the developed regions of the world including the US, that percentage will be closer to 90%. Already, 86% of Texans live in cities, and the urban population of the state is projected to double within the next 40 years. This urban growth will put unprecedented pressure on natural resources, especially water.\n\nWater will be needed for domestic and industrial use within cities, and it will be needed to generate electricity and grow food to support urban populations. Of considerable concern is the fact that more than half of the world\u2019s cities are situated in water basins that are already experiencing water shortages. In most of those water-stressed basins, more than 90% of water consumed goes to irrigated agriculture. This suggests both the need and the opportunity for cities to collaborate with farmers to implement water-saving measures on agricultural lands. Such urban-rural partnerships promise to reduce the risk of shortages for all water users, and in some cases the water saved in agriculture can be used to support growing urban demands.\n\nIt will be a huge challenge to secure the health of freshwater ecosystems while meeting the growing water demands of cities. Progressive policies are urgently needed to stop or reverse the depletion of freshwater sources, imperilment of aquatic species, and degradation of ecosystem services. This presentation will highlight some hopeful approaches drawn from water basins around the world.", "type": "status", "id": "270115323088033_341840819248816", "status_type": "mobile_status_update"}

{"picture": "https://fbcdn-photos-g-a.akamaihd.net/hphotos-ak-prn1/t1.0-0/22089_328929620539936_639306749_s.jpg", "from": {"category": "University", "name": "Texas A&M Wildlife and Fisheries Sciences", "category_list": [{"id": "108051929285833", "name": "College & University"}], "id": "270115323088033"}, "privacy": {"value": ""}, "actions": [{"link": "https://www.facebook.com/270115323088033/posts/328929650539933", "name": "Comment"}, {"link": "https://www.facebook.com/270115323088033/posts/328929650539933", "name": "Like"}], "updated_time": "2013-01-29T15:26:40+0000", "link": "https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=328929620539936&set=a.277933622306203.47638.270115323088033&type=1&relevant_count=1", "object_id": "328929620539936", "created_time": "2013-01-29T15:26:40+0000", "message": "ABS Seminar, Tuesday, Jan. 29, 4:00 - 5:00 pm, 1400 Memorial Student Center (MSC)\r\nMission Accomplished or Mission Impossible: Predicting The Biological Impacts of Climate Change\r\nPresented by Dr. Jonathan Newman , School of Environmental Sciences, University of Guelph \r\n*Co-sponsored by the Department of Philosophy\u2019s Applied Ethics Initiative\r\n\r\nIn the early 1990s climate change, or global warming as it was more commonly known then, was not the hot topic (pardon the pun) in ecology that it is today. The journal Ecology published just 26 papers on the subject during the first five years of the 1990s, compared to the 467 published in the last five years. I personally was not interested in the topic. I considered it a somewhat fringe area of work within the mainstream of ecological research. Nevertheless, some colleagues convinced me to apply for a grant to work on the subject with them, so I started doing some reading. I came across an edited book called Biotic Interactions and Global Change (1993); in the introduction, the editors laid down the challenge for ecologists:\r\n\r\n\r\n\u201c\u2026 they [fragmentation & climate change] represent crucial test cases for the science of ecology and evolutionary biology.\r\n\r\n\u2026 if we as community ecologists cannot predict the patterns of diversity change associated with these global onslaughts, one has to wonder just what community ecology can predict.\u201d\r\n\r\n\u2013 Peter Kareiva, Joel Kingsolver & Raymond Huey (1993, pg 6)\r\n\r\nThis struck me as a potential indictment of my discipline. I believed (and still do) that ecology is a predictive science, and if that is true then we should certainly be\r\nable to meet Kareiva et al.\u2019s challenge! So I slowly started to work on the question \u201care the ecological impacts of climate change predictable?\u201d Notice that this question is subtly but importantly different from the question: \u201cwhat will be the ecological impacts of climate change?\u201d Over the years I have thought long and hard about the first question, and of course this necessitated thinking about the second as well. In this presentation I will illuminate, using examples from my own research and that of others, the very real difficulties that ecologists face in providing meaningful and robust predictions of the biological impacts of climate change. I will conclude, to co-opt a quote from the artist Francis Bacon, that I am: \u201cOptimistic, and utterly without hope.\u201d\r\n\r\nPhoto of Dr. Newman's Book, Climate Change Biology. Book available for purchase here: http://bookshop.cabi.org/?site=191&page=2633&pid=2267", "type": "photo", "id": "270115323088033_328929650539933", "status_type": "added_photos", "icon": "https://fbstatic-a.akamaihd.net/rsrc.php/v2/yz/r/StEh3RhPvjk.gif"}

It's an amazing feeling when you find yourself no more that eight to ten feet away from a bobcat. A mixture of fear and excitement. Bobcats usualy aren't aggressive but you never want to startle a wild animal. When I did start shooting, it took him several clicks to figure out what I was. He growled a low growl to warn me, then he relaxed as if he could care less.", "application": {"name": "Links", "id": "2309869772"}, "link": "https://www.facebook.com/photo.php?fbid=3633285438862&set=o.48009558692&type=1", "object_id": "3633285438862", "story_tags": {"0": [{"length": 41, "offset": 0, "type": "page", "id": "270115323088033", "name": "Texas A&M Wildlife and Fisheries Sciences"}], "49": [{"length": 11, "offset": 49, "type": "user", "id": "1475956557", "name": "Gary Stubbs"}]}, "created_time": "2012-09-03T13:22:41+0000", "message": "A curious bobcat near Texas Parks and Wildlife - Martin Creek Lake State Park in east Texas.
